results.occurrenceRemarks: Southern Cattails are one of two species we have at Coleto Creek Park. Common Cattails being the other.   Herbaceous, rhizomatous, perennial plants with long green slender stalks, topped with brown fluffy flowering heads.   The spike like, terminal, inflorescence has staminate flowers above and pistillate flowers below. This means that male and female flowers are on the same plant. the male part is at the top and the female part is underneath, as you will see in the pictures I took here.  Uses: Wildlife, wetland restoration, waste water tertiary treatment, possible food supply globally  Ethnobotanical: Baskets, matting, bedding material, ceremonial bundles, caulking material, cordage. All parts of the cattail are edible when gathered at the appropriate time of growth. Young shoots are cut from rhizomes in the spring. The base of the stem where it attaches to e rhizome can be boiled or roasted like potatoes.  Wildlife: Shelter and nesting cover for long- billed marsh wrens, red- wing blackbirds, yellow- headed black birds.  FUN FACT: Cattail pollen is a substitute for flour, it is a bright yellow or green color and turns pancakes, cookies and biscuits a pretty yellow color!
